{"title":"Can Vision Language Models Understand Mimed Actions?","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"There is no focused benchmark to test whether vision-language models can recognize human actions when salient contextual objects are absent, making it hard to isolate true gesture understanding from background or prop cues.","method":"Introduce MIME, a video-based QA benchmark of 86 mimed actions built from motion-capture retargeted to 3D characters and rendered for systematic remixing. Each action has 10 controlled variants by perturbing character (male/female/adversarial suit), background (aligned, misaligned, blank), and viewpoint (0°, 90°, 180°, 270°), totaling 860 samples. MIME supports both multiple-choice (choice condition) and free-form short answers (naming condition), enabling robust ablations of recognition under different contexts and angles (Fig. 2–3; §§2.1–2.3, 3.1)."},{"problem":"Do current VLMs genuinely understand human gestures, or do they rely on contextual shortcuts?","method":"Evaluate diverse open and API VLMs and humans on MIME and a control set, REAL, which contains live-action videos of the same actions with full context. Humans perform near-perfectly on both, but VLMs drop sharply on MIME (e.g., best zero-shot 52.3% MC and 19.8% FF), and under adversarial settings many models fall below 10%. Aligned backgrounds strongly boost accuracy while misaligned/blank harm it, indicating reliance on scene context rather than motion (Fig. 5; Table 1; §4.1–4.2)."},{"problem":"Can prompting or light adaptation improve VLM mime recognition, and where do models fail?","method":"Test Chain-of-Thought, few-shot in-context learning, and small-scale fine-tuning. Few-shot ICL notably boosts API models in MC (e.g., GPT-4o Mini from 41.9% to 74.4% on base; up to 94.2% with aligned background), but FF remains low; fine-tuning on small splits shows little/no gains (Table 4; §5.1–5.2). A failure-mode analysis of Gemini 1.5 Flash with CoT shows most errors stem from incorrect motion descriptions (54% partially correct, 16% completely incorrect) rather than only misinterpretation; aligned backgrounds correct 43% of prior errors, while misaligned backgrounds induce 24% confusion (§5.3)."}]}
